<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · What we service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">High-volume rack conveyor dishwashers, 200 to 400 racks an hour.</h2>

    <p>Rack conveyor dishwashers are the backbone of high-volume restaurant kitchens. Racks of dishes ride a chain conveyor through pre-rinse, wash, and final-rinse zones, throughput 200 to 400 racks per hour depending on machine size. Three platforms dominate LA: <strong>Hobart CRS</strong> (CRS-66A standard, CRS-86A larger, ITW Food Equipment Group), <strong>Champion 86 series</strong> (Ali Group, sister brand to Scotsman ice and Beverage-Air), and <strong>Jackson AJ-66</strong> (Hoshizaki America acquired the Jackson dishwasher line, now under Hoshizaki commercial umbrella). Plus Insinger and Stero on older installs.</p>

    <p>This is not the same machine as a flight-type institutional unit (continuous flight of pegs, 1,000+ dishes/hour, hospital and university scale) and not the same as an undercounter unit (30 to 40 racks/hour, bar and café scale). Different drive systems, different repair patterns. See <a href="/commercial/dishwasher-repair/flight-type-dishwasher-repair/">flight type dishwasher repair</a> and <a href="/commercial/dishwasher-repair/undercounter-dishwasher-repair/">undercounter commercial dishwasher repair</a>.</p>

    <p>BHGS #A49573. EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. $120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair, no emergency surcharge.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical rack conveyor failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Eight failure modes account for nearly every service call.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Conveyor motor seizure (year 5 to 8).</strong> Hobart CRS-66A, Champion 86, Jackson AJ-66 all use 1/3 to 1/2 HP gearmotor on the drive sprocket. Heat plus continuous load wears bearings. Replacement $480 to $720 part plus 1.5 to 2 hour labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Drive chain stretch and sprocket wear.</strong> Chain elongates, jumps a tooth, conveyor stutters. Replace chain plus drive sprocket as a system on year 7+ units. $400 to $600.</li>
      <li><strong>Wash arm jets clogged with mineral scale.</strong> Hard SoCal water scales the upper and lower wash arms. Cleaning service plus jet inspection. $200 to $360 standalone, often packaged with other work.</li>
      <li><strong>Booster heater element failure or scale buildup.</strong> Final rinse must hit 180°F per NSF and county health code (LADPH, OC Health Care Agency). Element burnout or heavy scale drops temp. $890 to $1,400 element replacement plus descale.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain solenoid or drain pump.</strong> Tank won't drain at end of cycle, water sits, next cycle starts dirty. Solenoid $260 to $380, drain pump $380 to $560.</li>
      <li><strong>Door switches and curtain switches.</strong> Safety interlocks at conveyor entry/exit. Worn micro-switches stop the machine mid-cycle. $200 to $340 per switch.</li>
      <li><strong>Conveyor speed sensor or pulse encoder.</strong> Modern Hobart CRS units monitor conveyor speed for cycle compliance. Sensor failure logs error, cycle aborts. $300 to $480.</li>
      <li><strong>Tank heater (electric or steam-injected).</strong> Wash tank holds 150 to 160°F for chemical sanitizing. Heater failure means undersized heat input, food doesn't sanitize. $700 to $1,200 depending on type.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
